critical_fixes.description:
storage_design.json specifies o_orderdate and l_shipdate use 'delta' encoding. The current code loads raw encoded values:
  const int32_t* o_orderdate_raw = (const int32_t*)mmapFile(gendb_dir + "/orders.o_orderdate.col", orders_size);
  const int32_t* l_shipdate_raw = (const int32_t*)mmapFile(gendb_dir + "/lineitem.l_shipdate.col", lineitem_size);

Then directly uses them in comparisons:
  if (...&& o_orderdate_raw[i] < orderdate_cutoff) { ... }
  if (...&& shipdate > shipdate_cutoff) { ... }

But delta-encoded values are NOT absolute dates. They are relative differences. Example: if day 1 is 9200 and delta is +4, the encoded value is 4, not 9204. Comparing delta values to absolute constants produces garbage results.

Fix: Before filtering, decode both columns via cumulative sum:
  std::vector<int32_t> o_orderdate_decoded(num_orders);
  o_orderdate_decoded[0] = o_orderdate_raw[0];
  for (size_t i = 1; i < num_orders; ++i)
    o_orderdate_decoded[i] = o_orderdate_decoded[i-1] + o_orderdate_raw[i];

Then use o_orderdate_decoded instead of o_orderdate_raw in all filtering. Do the same for l_shipdate.

performance_optimizations.description:
Vectorize the l_shipdate > 9204 check using AVX2 (compare 4 int32_t in parallel):

```cpp
const __m128i mask = _mm_set1_epi32(shipdate_cutoff);
for (size_t j = 0; j < num_lineitems - 3; j += 4) {
  __m128i dates = _mm_loadu_si128((__m128i*)&decoded_shipdate[j]);
  __m128i cmp = _mm_cmpgt_epi32(dates, mask);
  // Process matches
}
```

Combine with partial aggregation per SIMD chunk to amortize overhead. This is a secondary optimization after parallelism.
